    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, I see! You were referring to the high-value electronics, not the goblin hoard. That makes perfect sense in the context of your warehouse.\n\nThe \"goblin hoard\" was just a metaphor I slipped into, thinking of how goblins are famously obsessed with hoarding shiny, valuable things like gold and gems. In your case, the micro-controllers and voltage regulators are the \"shiny things\" that goblins would fight over.\n\nSo, to answer your question about handling high-value electronics: you should probably implement a stricter access control system, perhaps requiring two people to sign off on any movement of these specific SKUs. You could also consider placing them in a secure, locked cabinet that only authorized personnel can open, much like a goblin's secret stash.\n\nAdditionally, since the variances are consistent, it might be worth checking if the barcode scanners are being used correctly. Sometimes, if a scanner is misaligned or dirty, it might read a wrong code, leading to the system thinking an item is still in the bin when it's actually been moved.\n\nWould you like me to suggest some specific software features that could help track these movements more closely?",
